{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"I got my first computer when I was a teenager growing up in Accra,"},{"time":5000,"text":"and it was a really cool device."},{"time":8000,"text":"You could play games with it. You could program it in BASIC."},{"time":13000,"text":"And I was fascinated."},{"time":15000,"text":"So I went into the library to figure out how did this thing work."},{"time":21000,"text":"I read about how the CPU is constantly shuffling data back and forth"},{"time":26000,"text":"between the memory, the RAM and the ALU,"},{"time":30000,"text":"the arithmetic and logic unit."},{"time":32000,"text":"And I thought to myself, this CPU really has to work like crazy"},{"time":36000,"text":"just to keep all this data moving through the system."}]},{"cues":[{"time":40000,"text":"But nobody was really worried about this."},{"time":43000,"text":"When computers were first introduced,"},{"time":45000,"text":"they were said to be a million times faster than neurons."},{"time":48000,"text":"People were really excited. They thought they would soon outstrip"},{"time":53000,"text":"the capacity of the brain."},{"time":56000,"text":"This is a quote, actually, from Alan Turing:"},{"time":59000,"text":"\"In 30 years, it will be as easy to ask a computer a question"},{"time":63000,"text":"as to ask a person.\""},{"time":65000,"text":"This was in 1946. And now, in 2007, it's still not true."},{"time":72000,"text":"And so, the question is, why aren't we really seeing"},{"time":76000,"text":"this kind of power in computers that we see in the brain?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":80000,"text":"What people didn't realize, and I'm just beginning to realize right now,"},{"time":84000,"text":"is that we pay a huge price for the speed"},{"time":86000,"text":"that we claim is a big advantage of these computers."},{"time":90000,"text":"Let's take a look at some numbers."},{"time":92000,"text":"This is Blue Gene, the fastest computer in the world."},{"time":96000,"text":"It's got 120,000 processors; they can basically process"},{"time":101000,"text":"10 quadrillion bits of information per second."},{"time":104000,"text":"That's 10 to the sixteenth. And they consume one and a half megawatts of power."},{"time":111000,"text":"So that would be really great, if you could add that"},{"time":114000,"text":"to the production capacity in Tanzania."},{"time":116000,"text":"It would really boost the economy."},{"time":118000,"text":"Just to go back to the States,"},{"time":122000,"text":"if you translate the amount of power or electricity"},{"time":124000,"text":"this computer uses to the amount of households in the States,"},{"time":127000,"text":"you get 1,200 households in the U.S."},{"time":131000,"text":"That's how much power this computer uses."}]},{"cues":[{"time":133000,"text":"Now, let's compare this with the brain."},{"time":136000,"text":"This is a picture of, actually Rory Sayres' girlfriend's brain."},{"time":141000,"text":"Rory is a graduate student at Stanford."},{"time":143000,"text":"He studies the brain using MRI, and he claims that"},{"time":147000,"text":"this is the most beautiful brain that he has ever scanned."},{"time":150000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":152000,"text":"So that's true love, right there."},{"time":155000,"text":"Now, how much computation does the brain do?"},{"time":158000,"text":"I estimate 10 to the 16 bits per second,"},{"time":160000,"text":"which is actually about very similar to what Blue Gene does."},{"time":164000,"text":"So that's the question. The question is, how much --"},{"time":166000,"text":"they are doing a similar amount of processing, similar amount of data --"},{"time":169000,"text":"the question is how much energy or electricity does the brain use?"},{"time":174000,"text":"And it's actually as much as your laptop computer:"},{"time":177000,"text":"it's just 10 watts."},{"time":179000,"text":"So what we are doing right now with computers"},{"time":182000,"text":"with the energy consumed by 1,200 houses,"},{"time":185000,"text":"the brain is doing with the energy consumed by your laptop."}]},{"cues":[{"time":190000,"text":"So the question is, how is the brain able to achieve this kind of efficiency?"},{"time":193000,"text":"And let me just summarize. So the bottom line:"},{"time":195000,"text":"the brain processes information using 100,000 times less energy"},{"time":199000,"text":"than we do right now with this computer technology that we have."},{"time":203000,"text":"How is the brain able to do this?"},{"time":205000,"text":"Let's just take a look about how the brain works,"},{"time":208000,"text":"and then I'll compare that with how computers work."},{"time":212000,"text":"So, this clip is from the PBS series, \"The Secret Life of the Brain.\""},{"time":216000,"text":"It shows you these cells that process information."},{"time":219000,"text":"They are called neurons."},{"time":220000,"text":"They send little pulses of electricity down their processes to each other,"},{"time":226000,"text":"and where they contact each other, those little pulses"},{"time":228000,"text":"of electricity can jump from one neuron to the other."},{"time":230000,"text":"That process is called a synapse."},{"time":233000,"text":"You've got this huge network of cells interacting with each other --"},{"time":235000,"text":"about 100 million of them,"},{"time":237000,"text":"sending about 10 quadrillion of these pulses around every second."},{"time":241000,"text":"And that's basically what's going on in your brain right now as you're watching this."}]},{"cues":[{"time":247000,"text":"How does that compare with the way computers work?"},{"time":249000,"text":"In the computer, you have all the data"},{"time":251000,"text":"going through the central processing unit,"},{"time":253000,"text":"and any piece of data basically has to go through that bottleneck,"},{"time":256000,"text":"whereas in the brain, what you have is these neurons,"},{"time":260000,"text":"and the data just really flows through a network of connections"},{"time":264000,"text":"among the neurons. There's no bottleneck here."},{"time":266000,"text":"It's really a network in the literal sense of the word."},{"time":270000,"text":"The net is doing the work in the brain."},{"time":274000,"text":"If you just look at these two pictures,"},{"time":276000,"text":"these kind of words pop into your mind."},{"time":278000,"text":"This is serial and it's rigid -- it's like cars on a freeway,"},{"time":282000,"text":"everything has to happen in lockstep --"},{"time":285000,"text":"whereas this is parallel and it's fluid."},{"time":287000,"text":"Information processing is very dynamic and adaptive."}]},{"cues":[{"time":290000,"text":"So I'm not the first to figure this out. This is a quote from Brian Eno:"},{"time":294000,"text":"\"the problem with computers is that there is not enough Africa in them.\""},{"time":298000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":304000,"text":"Brian actually said this in 1995."},{"time":307000,"text":"And nobody was listening then,"},{"time":310000,"text":"but now people are beginning to listen"},{"time":312000,"text":"because there's a pressing, technological problem that we face."},{"time":317000,"text":"And I'll just take you through that a little bit in the next few slides."}]},{"cues":[{"time":322000,"text":"This is -- it's actually really this remarkable convergence"},{"time":326000,"text":"between the devices that we use to compute in computers,"},{"time":331000,"text":"and the devices that our brains use to compute."},{"time":335000,"text":"The devices that computers use are what's called a transistor."},{"time":339000,"text":"This electrode here, called the gate, controls the flow of current"},{"time":343000,"text":"from the source to the drain -- these two electrodes."},{"time":346000,"text":"And that current, electrical current,"},{"time":348000,"text":"is carried by electrons, just like in your house and so on."},{"time":354000,"text":"And what you have here is, when you actually turn on the gate,"},{"time":359000,"text":"you get an increase in the amount of current, and you get a steady flow of current."},{"time":363000,"text":"And when you turn off the gate, there's no current flowing through the device."},{"time":367000,"text":"Your computer uses this presence of current to represent a one,"},{"time":372000,"text":"and the absence of current to represent a zero."}]},{"cues":[{"time":376000,"text":"Now, what's happening is that as transistors are getting smaller and smaller and smaller,"},{"time":382000,"text":"they no longer behave like this."},{"time":384000,"text":"In fact, they are starting to behave like the device that neurons use to compute,"},{"time":389000,"text":"which is called an ion channel."},{"time":391000,"text":"And this is a little protein molecule."},{"time":393000,"text":"I mean, neurons have thousands of these."},{"time":397000,"text":"And it sits in the membrane of the cell and it's got a pore in it."},{"time":401000,"text":"And these are individual potassium ions"},{"time":404000,"text":"that are flowing through that pore."},{"time":406000,"text":"Now, this pore can open and close."},{"time":408000,"text":"But, when it's open, because these ions have to line up"},{"time":413000,"text":"and flow through, one at a time, you get a kind of sporadic, not steady --"},{"time":418000,"text":"it's a sporadic flow of current."},{"time":421000,"text":"And even when you close the pore -- which neurons can do,"},{"time":424000,"text":"they can open and close these pores to generate electrical activity --"},{"time":429000,"text":"even when it's closed, because these ions are so small,"},{"time":432000,"text":"they can actually sneak through, a few can sneak through at a time."},{"time":435000,"text":"So, what you have is that when the pore is open,"},{"time":438000,"text":"you get some current sometimes."},{"time":440000,"text":"These are your ones, but you've got a few zeros thrown in."},{"time":443000,"text":"And when it's closed, you have a zero,"},{"time":447000,"text":"but you have a few ones thrown in."}]},{"cues":[{"time":450000,"text":"Now, this is starting to happen in transistors."},{"time":453000,"text":"And the reason why that's happening is that, right now, in 2007 --"},{"time":458000,"text":"the technology that we are using -- a transistor is big enough"},{"time":462000,"text":"that several electrons can flow through the channel simultaneously, side by side."},{"time":467000,"text":"In fact, there's about 12 electrons can all be flowing this way."},{"time":471000,"text":"And that means that a transistor corresponds"},{"time":473000,"text":"to about 12 ion channels in parallel."},{"time":476000,"text":"Now, in a few years time, by 2015, we will shrink transistors so much."},{"time":481000,"text":"This is what Intel does to keep adding more cores onto the chip."},{"time":486000,"text":"Or your memory sticks that you have now can carry one gigabyte"},{"time":489000,"text":"of stuff on them -- before, it was 256."},{"time":491000,"text":"Transistors are getting smaller to allow this to happen,"},{"time":494000,"text":"and technology has really benefitted from that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":497000,"text":"But what's happening now is that in 2015, the transistor is going to become so small,"},{"time":502000,"text":"that it corresponds to only one electron at a time"},{"time":505000,"text":"can flow through that channel,"},{"time":507000,"text":"and that corresponds to a single ion channel."},{"time":509000,"text":"And you start having the same kind of traffic jams that you have in the ion channel."},{"time":513000,"text":"The current will turn on and off at random,"},{"time":516000,"text":"even when it's supposed to be on."},{"time":518000,"text":"And that means your computer is going to get"},{"time":520000,"text":"its ones and zeros mixed up, and that's going to crash your machine."}]},{"cues":[{"time":524000,"text":"So, we are at the stage where we"},{"time":528000,"text":"don't really know how to compute with these kinds of devices."},{"time":531000,"text":"And the only kind of thing -- the only thing we know right now"},{"time":534000,"text":"that can compute with these kinds of devices are the brain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":537000,"text":"OK, so a computer picks a specific item of data from memory,"},{"time":541000,"text":"it sends it into the processor or the ALU,"},{"time":544000,"text":"and then it puts the result back into memory."},{"time":546000,"text":"That's the red path that's highlighted."},{"time":548000,"text":"The way brains work, I told you all, you have got all these neurons."},{"time":552000,"text":"And the way they represent information is"},{"time":554000,"text":"they break up that data into little pieces"},{"time":556000,"text":"that are represented by pulses and different neurons."},{"time":559000,"text":"So you have all these pieces of data"},{"time":561000,"text":"distributed throughout the network."},{"time":563000,"text":"And then the way that you process that data to get a result"},{"time":566000,"text":"is that you translate this pattern of activity into a new pattern of activity,"},{"time":570000,"text":"just by it flowing through the network."},{"time":573000,"text":"So you set up these connections"},{"time":575000,"text":"such that the input pattern just flows"},{"time":578000,"text":"and generates the output pattern."}]},{"cues":[{"time":580000,"text":"What you see here is that there's these redundant connections."},{"time":584000,"text":"So if this piece of data or this piece of the data gets clobbered,"},{"time":588000,"text":"it doesn't show up over here, these two pieces can activate the missing part"},{"time":593000,"text":"with these redundant connections."},{"time":595000,"text":"So even when you go to these crappy devices"},{"time":597000,"text":"where sometimes you want a one and you get a zero, and it doesn't show up,"},{"time":600000,"text":"there's redundancy in the network"},{"time":602000,"text":"that can actually recover the missing information."},{"time":605000,"text":"It makes the brain inherently robust."},{"time":608000,"text":"What you have here is a system where you store data locally."},{"time":611000,"text":"And it's brittle, because each of these steps has to be flawless,"},{"time":615000,"text":"otherwise you lose that data, whereas in the brain, you have a system"},{"time":618000,"text":"that stores data in a distributed way, and it's robust."}]},{"cues":[{"time":622000,"text":"What I want to basically talk about is my dream,"},{"time":626000,"text":"which is to build a computer that works like the brain."},{"time":629000,"text":"This is something that we've been working on for the last couple of years."},{"time":633000,"text":"And I'm going to show you a system that we designed"},{"time":636000,"text":"to model the retina,"},{"time":639000,"text":"which is a piece of brain that lines the inside of your eyeball."},{"time":644000,"text":"We didn't do this by actually writing code, like you do in a computer."},{"time":650000,"text":"In fact, the processing that happens"},{"time":653000,"text":"in that little piece of brain is very similar"},{"time":655000,"text":"to the kind of processing that computers"},{"time":656000,"text":"do when they stream video over the Internet."},{"time":660000,"text":"They want to compress the information --"},{"time":661000,"text":"they just want to send the changes, what's new in the image, and so on --"},{"time":665000,"text":"and that is how your eyeball"},{"time":668000,"text":"is able to squeeze all that information down to your optic nerve,"},{"time":671000,"text":"to send to the rest of the brain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":673000,"text":"Instead of doing this in software, or doing those kinds of algorithms,"},{"time":676000,"text":"we went and talked to neurobiologists"},{"time":679000,"text":"who have actually reverse engineered that piece of brain that's called the retina."},{"time":683000,"text":"And they figured out all the different cells,"},{"time":685000,"text":"and they figured out the network, and we just took that network"},{"time":688000,"text":"and we used it as the blueprint for the design of a silicon chip."},{"time":692000,"text":"So now the neurons are represented by little nodes or circuits on the chip,"},{"time":698000,"text":"and the connections among the neurons are represented, actually modeled by transistors."},{"time":703000,"text":"And these transistors are behaving essentially"},{"time":705000,"text":"just like ion channels behave in the brain."},{"time":708000,"text":"It will give you the same kind of robust architecture that I described."}]},{"cues":[{"time":713000,"text":"Here is actually what our artificial eye looks like."},{"time":717000,"text":"The retina chip that we designed sits behind this lens here."},{"time":722000,"text":"And the chip -- I'm going to show you a video"},{"time":724000,"text":"that the silicon retina put out of its output"},{"time":727000,"text":"when it was looking at Kareem Zaghloul,"},{"time":730000,"text":"who's the student who designed this chip."},{"time":732000,"text":"Let me explain what you're going to see, OK,"},{"time":734000,"text":"because it's putting out different kinds of information,"},{"time":737000,"text":"it's not as straightforward as a camera."},{"time":739000,"text":"The retina chip extracts four different kinds of information."},{"time":742000,"text":"It extracts regions with dark contrast,"},{"time":745000,"text":"which will show up on the video as red."},{"time":748000,"text":"And it extracts regions with white or light contrast,"},{"time":752000,"text":"which will show up on the video as green."}]},{"cues":[{"time":754000,"text":"This is Kareem's dark eyes"},{"time":756000,"text":"and that's the white background that you see here."},{"time":759000,"text":"And then it also extracts movement."},{"time":761000,"text":"When Kareem moves his head to the right,"},{"time":763000,"text":"you will see this blue activity there;"},{"time":765000,"text":"it represents regions where the contrast is increasing in the image,"},{"time":768000,"text":"that's where it's going from dark to light."},{"time":771000,"text":"And you also see this yellow activity,"},{"time":773000,"text":"which represents regions where contrast is decreasing;"},{"time":777000,"text":"it's going from light to dark."},{"time":779000,"text":"And these four types of information --"},{"time":782000,"text":"your optic nerve has about a million fibers in it,"},{"time":786000,"text":"and 900,000 of those fibers"},{"time":789000,"text":"send these four types of information."},{"time":791000,"text":"So we are really duplicating the kind of signals that you have on the optic nerve."}]},{"cues":[{"time":795000,"text":"What you notice here is that these snapshots"},{"time":798000,"text":"taken from the output of the retina chip are very sparse, right?"},{"time":802000,"text":"It doesn't light up green everywhere in the background,"},{"time":804000,"text":"only on the edges, and then in the hair, and so on."},{"time":807000,"text":"And this is the same thing you see"},{"time":808000,"text":"when people compress video to send: they want to make it very sparse,"},{"time":812000,"text":"because that file is smaller. And this is what the retina is doing,"},{"time":815000,"text":"and it's doing it just with the circuitry, and how this network of neurons"},{"time":819000,"text":"that are interacting in there, which we've captured on the chip."}]},{"cues":[{"time":822000,"text":"But the point that I want to make -- I'll show you up here."},{"time":825000,"text":"So this image here is going to look like these ones,"},{"time":828000,"text":"but here I'll show you that we can reconstruct the image,"},{"time":830000,"text":"so, you know, you can almost recognize Kareem in that top part there."},{"time":835000,"text":"And so, here you go."},{"time":846000,"text":"Yes, so that's the idea."},{"time":849000,"text":"When you stand still, you just see the light and dark contrasts."},{"time":851000,"text":"But when it's moving back and forth,"},{"time":853000,"text":"the retina picks up these changes."},{"time":856000,"text":"And that's why, you know, when you're sitting here"},{"time":857000,"text":"and something happens in your background,"},{"time":859000,"text":"you merely move your eyes to it."},{"time":861000,"text":"There are these cells that detect change"},{"time":863000,"text":"and you move your attention to it."},{"time":865000,"text":"So those are very important for catching somebody"},{"time":867000,"text":"who's trying to sneak up on you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":869000,"text":"Let me just end by saying that this is what happens"},{"time":872000,"text":"when you put Africa in a piano, OK."},{"time":875000,"text":"This is a steel drum here that has been modified,"},{"time":878000,"text":"and that's what happens when you put Africa in a piano."},{"time":881000,"text":"And what I would like us to do is put Africa in the computer,"},{"time":885000,"text":"and come up with a new kind of computer"},{"time":887000,"text":"that will generate thought, imagination, be creative and things like that."},{"time":890000,"text":"Thank you."},{"time":892000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":894000,"text":"Chris Anderson: Question for you, Kwabena."},{"time":896000,"text":"Do you put together in your mind the work you're doing,"},{"time":900000,"text":"the future of Africa, this conference --"},{"time":903000,"text":"what connections can we make, if any, between them?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":906000,"text":"Kwabena Boahen: Yes, like I said at the beginning,"},{"time":908000,"text":"I got my first computer when I was a teenager, growing up in Accra."},{"time":912000,"text":"And I had this gut reaction that this was the wrong way to do it."},{"time":916000,"text":"It was very brute force; it was very inelegant."},{"time":919000,"text":"I don't think that I would've had that reaction,"},{"time":921000,"text":"if I'd grown up reading all this science fiction,"},{"time":924000,"text":"hearing about RD2D2, whatever it was called, and just -- you know,"},{"time":928000,"text":"buying into this hype about computers."},{"time":929000,"text":"I was coming at it from a different perspective,"},{"time":931000,"text":"where I was bringing that different perspective"},{"time":933000,"text":"to bear on the problem."},{"time":935000,"text":"And I think a lot of people in Africa have this different perspective,"},{"time":938000,"text":"and I think that's going to impact technology."},{"time":940000,"text":"And that's going to impact how it's going to evolve."},{"time":942000,"text":"And I think you're going to be able to see, use that infusion,"},{"time":944000,"text":"to come up with new things,"},{"time":946000,"text":"because you're coming from a different perspective."},{"time":949000,"text":"I think we can contribute. We can dream like everybody else."}]},{"cues":[{"time":953000,"text":"CA: Thanks Kwabena, that was really interesting."},{"time":955000,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":956000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}